# =============================================================================
# QUIET AND JSON MODE BEHAVIOR
# =============================================================================
#
# --quiet / -q :
#   Suppresses all non-error output (info, success, warnings, help text, status, etc.).
#   Only critical errors are shown (as plain text or JSON error object).
#
# --json :
#   Enables strict machine-readable JSON output.
#   Automatically implies --quiet.
#   The script MUST output EXACTLY ONE valid JSON object per execution.
#   Never output more than one JSON object or any other text.
#
#   JSON Output Rules (strict):
#   - Always starts with {"type": "success|status|error|list|stats|about|version|...", ...}
#   - "message" field is optional — only include when it adds real value.
#   - All numbers (duration, remaining, minutes, seconds, percent, count, etc.) must be unquoted.
#   - Names, modes, phases, and themes are always strings.
#   - Status objects should include "duration", "remaining", and "percent" when relevant.
#   - Use "expired": true when a pomodoro has reached zero.
#
#   Supported "type" values:
#     success, status, error, list, stats, about, version
#
#   Recommended JSON Examples (pomo specific):
#
#   Success start:
#   {"type":"success","name":"focus","mode":"volatile","phase":"work","duration":3000,"remaining":3000,"work_minutes":50}
#
#   Status running:
#   {"type":"status","name":"default","mode":"persistent","phase":"work","phase_name":"Work","duration":1500,"remaining":487,"minutes":8,"seconds":7,"percent":67}
#
#   Status expired:
#   {"type":"status","name":"meeting","mode":"volatile","phase":"work","remaining":0,"expired":true}
#
#   List:
#   {"type":"list","mode":"both","count":2,"timers":[{...},{...}]}
#
#   Stats:
#   {"type":"stats","date":"2026-04-05","completed":7,"total_minutes":185}
#
#   Error:
#   {"type":"error","message":"No pomodoro 'foo' running.","code":"no_pomodoro"}
#
#   About / Version:
#   {"type":"about","version":"1.6.0","installed":"true","shell":"bash",...}
#
# Important Notes:
#   - The "watch" command does NOT support --json (it is interactive only).
#   - When both --quiet and --json are used, --json takes precedence.
#   - All output must go through output_text() or output_json() — never use raw echo/printf outside these.
#
# !!! DO NOT REMOVE OR SIMPLIFY THIS COMMENT !!!
# It serves as the canonical specification for quiet/JSON behavior and is referenced
